<paragraph blockId="55.[151,1059,1047,1157]" pageId="55" pageNumber="1014">
D i a g n o s i s: The specimens of this species most closely approximate those of 
<emphasis box="[151,394,1077,1098]" italics="true" pageId="55" pageNumber="1014">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pic" authorityYear="1950" box="[151,275,1077,1098]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Pujoliclerus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="55" pageNumber="1019" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Pujoliclerus</taxonomicName>
aspigalbus
</emphasis>
OPITZ from which 
<taxonomicName box="[609,721,1077,1098]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Pujoliclerus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="55" pageNumber="1014" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavidus">
<emphasis box="[609,721,1077,1098]" italics="true" pageId="55" pageNumber="1014">P. flavidus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
specimens differ by showing a much more elongated body, infuscated pronotal collar, and the elytral apex is yellow. The genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pic" authorityYear="1950" box="[262,386,1135,1156]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Pujoliclerus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="55" pageNumber="1019" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[262,386,1135,1156]" italics="true" pageId="55" pageNumber="1014">Pujoliclerus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
PIC was revised in 2014 (
<bibRefCitation author="OPITZ W" box="[648,783,1135,1157]" pageId="55" pageNumber="1014" pagination="727 - 756" refId="ref53564" refString="OPITZ W. (2014 d): Classification, natural history, and evolution of the checkered beetle genus Pujoliclerus PIC (Coleoptera: Cleridae: Peloniinae). - The Coleopteristss Bulletin 68 (4): 727 - 756." type="journal article" year="2014">OPITZ 2014d</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="55.[151,1059,1172,1459]" pageId="55" pageNumber="1014">
D e s c r i p t i o n: Size: Length 
<quantity box="[516,597,1172,1194]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.5" pageId="55" pageNumber="1014" unit="mm" value="4.5">4.5 mm</quantity>
; width 
<quantity box="[673,753,1173,1195]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.6" pageId="55" pageNumber="1014" unit="mm" value="1.6">1.6 mm</quantity>
. Form: As in 
<figureCitation box="[895,980,1173,1195]" captionStart="Figs 342-345" captionStartId="113.[151,191,1528,1550]" captionTargetBox="[154,1061,201,1516]" captionTargetId="figure@113.[153,1061,201,1516]" captionTargetPageId="113" captionText="Figs 342-345: Habitus; (342) Pujoliclerus dexus; (343) P. flavidus; (344) P. lasiosus; (345) P. melonius." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3746834" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3746834/files/figure.png" pageId="55" pageNumber="1014">Fig. 343</figureCitation>
. Color: Forebody yellow, except pronotal collar infuscated; antenna black; pterothorax and abdomen brown; elytra mostly black, epipleural margin and elytral apex yellow; legs mostly yellow, prothoracic tibiae and tarsi infuscated. Head: Cranium coarsely punctate; antenna (
<figureCitation box="[253,336,1290,1312]" captionStart="Figs 1-27" captionStartId="70.[151,191,1302,1324]" captionTargetBox="[155,1057,207,1268]" captionTargetId="figure@70.[155,1058,207,1283]" captionTargetPageId="70" captionText="Figs 1-27: Antennae; (1) Aphelocerus nodus; (2) A. copanus; (3) A. magnipannus; (4) A. yoro; (5) A. sparicapillus; (6) A. tigra. (7) A. nolus; (8) A. ligulus; (9) Perilypus schusteri; (10) P. apunctus; (11) P. virgulatus; (12) P. izabal; (13) P. alpinus; (14) Cregya fuscomacula; (15) Phonius versus; (16) Pujoliclerus ariquemes; (17) Pelonium falcatum; (18) Pujoliclerus cnecostus; (19) P. trunculus. (20) P. sentus; (21) P. testudinatus; (22) P. catie; (23) P. flavidus; (24) P. convexus; (25) P. meloinus; (26) P. mexicoensis; (27) P. tuxtlas." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3746746" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3746746/files/figure.png" pageId="55" pageNumber="1014">Fig. 23</figureCitation>
) capitate, funicular antennomeres shorter to capitulum, capitular antennomeres extraordinarily oblong/subrectangulate; eyes large, coarsely facetted, eye as wide as frons (EW/FW 25/25). Thorax: Pronotum (
<figureCitation box="[752,846,1349,1371]" captionStart="Figs 101-117" captionStartId="75.[151,191,1477,1499]" captionTargetBox="[152,1030,198,1448]" captionTargetId="figure@75.[152,1030,198,1465]" captionTargetPageId="75" captionText="Figs 101-117: Pronota; (101) Aphelocerus ligulus; (102) A. yoro; (103) Ridica achira; (104) R. merida; (105) Ampleris cacuminis; (106) Plocamocera catalexis; (107) Aphelocerus tigra; (108) A. sparicapillus; (109) A. nolus; (110) A. magnipannus; (111) Pyticeroides desodes; (112) Cregya petalosa; (113) C. livida; (114) C. tobagoensis; (115) C. maura; (116) Pujoliclerus flavidus; (117) Amboakis collucoatis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3746756" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3746756/files/figure.png" pageId="55" pageNumber="1014">Fig. 116</figureCitation>
) slightly transverse (PW/PL 70/65), disc finely punctate at disc, more coarsely punctate at sides, lateral tubercles well developed; elytra sculptured with 10 striae of asetiferous punctures (EL/EW 190/55). Abdomen: Pygidium scutiform.
</paragraph>
